courses.learning_outcomes:
Students will be able to:
1. Apply functional health pattern framework in studying physical and bio-psychosocial care of paediatric, adolescent and adult clients with alternations in medical/surgical conditions;
2. Perform comprehensive and focused health assessment of clients with altered functional patterns;
3. Critically analyze assessment data to diagnose acute and potential alternations in functional health patterns;
4. Apply principles and research evidence from biological, behavioural and nursing sciences in planning care for clients with:
- accident and emergency care;
- alternations in paediatric & adolescence health conditions; or
- alternations in eye, ear, nose and throat conditions
5. Integrate nursing care plan with psychosocial and cultural considerations; and
6. Apply psychosocial support and interventions in caring for clients and families experiencing moderate to severe health problems.

Students will be able to:
1. Apply the functional health pattern framework in studying physical and bio-psychosocial care of clients with alternations in mental, cardiac and other medical/surgical conditions;
2. Further develop comprehensive and focus health assessment skills for clients with altered functional patterns and/or mental health problems;
3. Critically analyze assessment data to diagnose alternations in mental and/or functional health patterns;
4. Apply principles and research evidence from biological, behavioural and nursing sciences in planning care for clients with:
- alternations in cardiovascular diseases;
- alternations in lymphatic functions;
- alternations in mental health functions;
5. Integrate nursing care planning with psychosocial and cultural considerations; and
6. Apply psychosocial support and interventions in caring for clients and families with physical and/or mental health problems.

The course will enable students to:
1. Analyse the implications of nursing knowledge for their chosen research topic;
2. Critically assess the contribution of the literature to their research study;
3. Analyse the appropriateness of different research designs to the context of the research study;
4. Justify the appropriateness of the sampling designs and methods selected for their research study;
5. Analyse and evaluate methods of data collection in the context of their research study;
6. Evaluate the contribution of different methods of data analysis to their research study;
7. Practise and evaluate a range of data collection and data analysis techniques;
8. Examine the processes of systematic reviews as the foundation for informed clinical practice.
9. Develop techniques to appraise, extract and pooling of data collected through the systematic review process.
10 Develop a proposal for their research study.

